content: Cool app

I think this game is "out-of-town" from my perspective. I love the hack-and- slash vibe that it puts from inspirations taken from Bloodborne, The Witcher and Star Wars Battlefront (Heroes vs Villains melee/lightsaber combat). To put this in a cellphone is great and the controls are pretty solid. Graphically, it looks appealing and the title of it doesn't sound so generic. One issue that I have with it though, is that it has too short of a campaign and the training mode can get very repetitive.

Really enjoyable little game. The combat is sound and satisfying. The biggest issue I had was that one ability overshadowed all the others - the one that knocks enemies down. Since all the other abilities are blocked much easier, but take more time to pull off, often they just weren't as good to use. While the game was a lot of fun, it's very short & there's no replay value. Also, the high scores in the Dojo section appear to be cheated, but it's not something that really affects anything.

I'm gonna be straightforward: when I think of mobile games, I never expect a fully fleshed out game free of ads, nag screens and in-app purchases. But this game has none of these! Excellent visuals, I mean seriously, it is such a delight to see cell shaded graphics in an era where everyone's competing for photorealism. The gameplay is simple, yet addicting and the frame rate maintains a buttery smooth flow, even on my Tab S, which is not a graphically robust as Snapdragon-equipped devices. The upgrades are fun, the environments varied, and the enemies can get pretty challenging. All in all, this is $3 well spent, and I wish the developers the best of luck for whatever future games they have planned.

I've enjoyed this game a lot. Towards the end it gets quite difficult, even on Amateur mode. What I didn't like is no replay value whatsoever, I wasn't even tempted to try the extra modes after I beat the game once. But we'll see. Dojo mode is really not what I expected, I suggest you guys add a mode where you kill as many soldiers as you can before your samurai drops. High scores and all. Because Dojo in itself isn't a very entertaining concept, especially when I can't see what level I'm on. Graphics are dark, smooth, and very interesting, cartoon textures reminds me of Otaku or Zelda: The Wind Waker. It's a very fun game to just plow through and it's very easily picked up and put down, which makes it nice for passing time. For $0.99 (it was on sale) I thought it was like, the best deal ever. At $2.99 it's still a nice deal, but when you have games like the new "Aralon" this is putting the game on a higher end spectrum. And it's an excellent game, as was every other MADFINGER title. Unfortunately it's lacking in the content department. If you expand on to it I'll be very satisfied. For now, awesome game, great graphics, low replay value, 4/5.

Fun game and very well drawn game.  Love the concept, but just as it starts getting "good" it ends and has very little replay value.  By the time you can get all the styles you are near to, or on the very last level.  The game just needs, more. Way more of these pretty levels. More enemy types, dogs, ninjas, and demons too!  Add more variations on the enemy encounters.  More ways to kill, such as throwing your own weapons.  More weapons...such as dual blades or nun-chucks.  How about being able to use save slots??    Re-tune those combos...heck the basic attacks are kinda, wonky and at times and that means you tend to rely on rock-paper-scissors approach to baddies.  Such as run behind the normal guys and strike for instant death...run from so-and-so until he does blah blah blah.    I paid only a dollar for it and at that price it's, still a 3 star game.  But, it's a heck of a start and if the dev adds more of what I'm mentioning above (currently only about 7 or 8) I'd happily rate it a solid 5 and recommend it to others.

The graphics are amazing, but the game is just your usual hack'n'slash. All you really ever do is queue up button combinations and dodge now and then. The camera is frustrating during some moments, particularly where you have to navigate through a bunch of death traps but you can't get a good grip on which parts are safe due to the perspective. As soon as you get Walking Death (XXOXX), the game becomes a literal cakewalk, and all you have to do is just run around, knock people down, stab them, rinse, repeat. This move is game-breaking, where before you would have to actually spend some time taking out enemies, this practically takes out any melee enemy that is even close to you at once as a guaranteed kill after you knock them down. Ultimately, these are just a couple of nitpicks, Samurai II: Vengeance is a solid, fun game.
